[7] Italy
Date: 5 May 2017
Source: Vivere Milano [machine translated, edited - Mod.SH]
http://viveremilano.biz/2017/05/05/morbillo-boom-di-casi-ad-aprile-5-volte-pi-del-2016/


The measles alarm continues in Italy, but in Calabria, one of the least affected regions, there have been only 18 cases this week, compared with last week [24 to 30 Apr 2017] when there were 29.

385 cases of measles were registered in Italy in April 2017; 5 times as many as occurred in the same month of 2016, when there were just 76. The virus hit all of Italy, but regions in the center and north of the country accounted for 92% of cases. The Istituto Superiore di SanitÃ  [ISS; higher institute of health] monitors weekly cases registered in the country and on 3 May 2017 released its latest bulletin http://www.epicentro.iss.it/problemi/morbillo/Infografica2017.asp. [see next report]

34 per cent of patients who have come into contact with measles have had at least one complication. 39 per cent were admitted to hospital; 15 per cent made use of the emergency room.

Giovanni Rezza, an immunologist at the ISS, explains: "Broadly speaking, measles does behave a bit like this. In the pre-vaccine era, there were epidemic waves every 2-3 years, in essence when a new susceptible population had been reconstituted. "[This year (2017), there are] 6 times more cases than in the 1st 4 months of 2016, a year in which cases numbered 859 in total. The most affected regions are Lazio (570 cases), Piedmont (429), Lombardy (241), Tuscany (236) and Veneto (135).

According to the latest data from the Ministry of Health, the average coverage for vaccinations against polio, tetanus, diphtheria, hepatitis B, pertussis, and _Haemophilus influenzae_ is 93.4 per cent, lower than in previous years (94.7 per cent in 2014, 95.7 per cent in 2013 and 96.1 per cent in 2012).

