<promed@promedmail.org>

[A HealthMap of France can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5019551,100.

The burden of disease from measles is entirely preventable and totally unnecessary. The increase in cases is largely a result of a study by Dr Andrew Wakefield (The Lancet February 1998), which has been refuted many times and was retracted by the journal that published it. Yet, anti-vaxxers continue to defend his views, and parents' fears push them to believe it. But the facts clearly support being exposed to the measles virus is a greater threat than any side effect or adverse reaction.

CDC estimates 146 000 deaths a year worldwide, mostly children, follow infection without vaccination. Global measles elimination is achievable and a public health priority. It is not sufficient to eliminate measles in developed countries alone, as one can see from the reports above, infected individuals carry the virus and expand the sphere of transmission wherever they travel. - Mod.LK]
